<ul>
<li><p>The author spends some time discussing language name, citing a number of names used by natives (including <em>Hindńę</em> and <em>RekÕühtah</em>) and a number of names coined by the British (including <em>Hindustani</em>). In the late 1700s, it appears that <em>Hindńę</em> was more often used to refer to the language, with <em>UrdŇę</em> or <em>UrdŇę-e mu‚ÄôallńĀ</em> referring to a place (the city of Delhi, the Mughal court, etc); this situation persists perhaps as late as the mid 1800s, since Shakespear‚Äôs 1849 dictionary does not recognize <em>UrdŇę</em> as a language name. The more complete <em>ZabńĀn-e urdŇę-e mu‚ÄôallńĀ</em> referred originally to Persian, but perhaps began referring to Hindustani under the reign of Shah ‚ÄôAlam II in the late 1700s, since he had a particular predilection for the language. The word <em>UrdŇę</em> as a language name took a while to establish, and it took even longer for <em>Hindńę</em> and <em>UrdŇę</em> to be used contrastively.</p>
<p>There is a narrative that the Arabic and Persian elements of the language was an artefact of ‚ÄúMuslim invaders and conquerors.‚ÄĚ The author objects strongly to this narrative, and cites many examples of its ubiquity in British writings. It appears for the first time in native writing in Mńęr Amman‚Äôs <em>BńĀń°-o-bahńĀr</em> (1803-1804). This text was intended mostly for a European audience, and appears to have misled otherwise competent and well-intentioned linguists (such as Grierson). Rather, the truer narrative is that the language, together with all of its indigenized Arabic and Persian elements, arose out of interactions of diverse people from all walks of life (scholars, poets, elite, plebian, etc).</p>
The author points out finally that heavily Sanskritized Hindi was resisted as late as the mid 1800s by educated Hindu speakers, and that the Sanskritization was partly an effort of the British.</li>
